name: Through the Bottom of the Glass
My Love Is Like a Red Red Rose
comments: Following the publication of The Red Red Rose in 1794 to Pietro Urbani's melody, the traditional words that Burns had poeticised were re-set to various other tunes in new publications.  For example, in James Johnson’s "The Scots Musical Museum", published shortly after Burns’s death in 1796, the lyric was set to a melody by the Scottish fiddler Niel Gow, entitled Major Graham’s Strathspey, which had appeared in Gow’s 1784 "A Collection of Strathspeys and Reels".  Johnson added a second version of the song entitled Old Set, Red, Red Rose, of which the old set referred to a tune called Mary Queen of Scots.  In 1799, George Thomson included the song in his publication "A Select Collection of Original Scottish Airs", this time to the air Wishaw’s Favourite, which was composed by the north-east English fiddler William Marshall.  Ultimately though, another Eighteenth Century tune, Low Down in the Broom , became the standard accompaniment we know today after the words and tune were matched in Volume 2 of Robert Archibald Smith's "The Scottish Minstrel - A Selection from the Vocal Melodies of Scotland" published in 1821.
adapted_from: Low Down in the Broom written by [Traditional] The Red Red Rose written by Robert Burns , [Traditional] , Pietro Urbani

name: Little Black Train
comments: Traditional song often associated with A.P. Carter who copyrighted it in the 1930s. However, neither the music nor the lyrics were original to him. In 1925, Dorothy Scarborough published a set of lyrics describing this song as a "Holy Roller song from Texas." Under the title "Judgement Train," a set of lyrics was published in 1916. A larger set of lyrics was published in 1907 with title "The Little Black Train." In his book "Long Steel Rail," Norm Cohen described the tune used by the Carter Family for "Little Black Train" as similar to the melody of "Roving Gambler."

name: Goodbye for Now
comments: Sondheim wrote the melody Goodbye for Now as a theme for Reds, Warren Beatty’s movie about the Russian Revolution. Some sources report that Beatty wanted co-star Diane Keaton to release the song as a single, so Sondheim added words, too. However, the vocal version was not released at the time. Sondheim said that the song was “an instrumental, not a vocal, and its tessitura (the preeminent areas of its range) was very wide; Diane couldn’t handle it comfortably – nor could many singers, without noticeably awkward shifts from head voice to chest voice.”

comments: Written for the musical revue Ain't Misbehavin', which opened at the Longacre Theatre on Broadway on May 9, 1978. The show ran for 1604 performances and won the Tony award for best musical. Goes like: "The night is getting on, the band is getting slow, the crowd is almost gone, but here we are still dancing. Nothing to do, but waltz. Our feet can barely move, my legs are yelling "Whoa", but we're in such a groove and love is still advancing. Nothing to do, but waltz. You can't suggest that we could go on jitterbugging, no bugging, we've nothing left for moves more strenuous than hugging, just hugging ..."

name: Sourwood Mountain
comments: Traditional American folk song that has been sung throughout the southern Appalachian mountains for well over 150 years. It has become a favorite of fiddlers as well as banjo players. The melody probably made its way to the US from the British Isles. The original ballad told the sad story of a young man who dies after being bitten by a snake. Later, the words were changed to describe flirting between boys and girls. Sourwood is another name for the chestnut tree; its bark is important for tanning leather.
